Parses `dict.steno`'s source text for three kinds of marker comments used to organize the viz UI's category tree, independent of the dictionary parser proper (this file only scans raw lines, not parsed entries).

Three marker syntaxes, distinguished by prefix-matching order since `##>` and `###` would otherwise also match a bare `##` check: `## label` starts a category persisting until the next `##` line; `##> label` starts a section that sub-divides a category's shared-stroke children until the next `##>` or `##`; `### text` describes only the single fence-open line that follows it (blank lines tolerated in between, any other content clears the pending description). `marker_label` explicitly rejects lines starting with `#` or `>` after the `##` prefix to avoid misclassifying the other two marker types.

Key functions: `scan(src) -> Vec<Marker>` and `scan_sections(src) -> Vec<Marker>` collect markers in file order with 1-based line numbers. `label_for(markers, entry_line) -> &str` finds the most recent preceding category marker, defaulting to `"Uncategorized"`. `section_for(sections, categories, entry_line) -> Option<&str>` returns the active section only if its marker line is more recent than the most recent category marker — this is how a section gets cleared when a new `##` category starts even without an intervening `##>`. `scan_desc(src) -> HashMap<usize, String>` maps a fence-open line's 1-based line number to its preceding `###` description text, using `is_fence_open` to detect a fence-open line as four backticks followed by non-empty content (distinguishing it from a bare closing fence of exactly four backticks).

No external dependencies beyond `std::collections::HashMap`. Callers elsewhere in `viz_data` presumably invoke `scan`/`scan_sections`/`scan_desc` once per file and pass results into `label_for`/`section_for` per entry.